title: How to make notes for the UPSC civil service, please read the detail below  - Quora

response.answer_text: Yes, I also agree that making notes is good practice for UPSC exams. Since syllabus is vast, notes can be used for later reference to reduce revision time. These are few points I can suggest for your question. You need not to make notes for each and every book you read. Few books written for UPSC consists each and every points important. In that case you may have to read the books again and again. Some books give lot of explanation. In such cases you can write core idea of the paragraph/page as one or two sentences.For example: Each and every point of the book Indian Polity by Lakshmikanth is important. I prefer reading the book again and again rather than making notes ( I mark important points using highlighter) In case of India since independence by Bipin chandra, I don't want to read 700 pages book again and again, so I made my own notes it. Recalling will take only 2-3% time required to read entire book.I didn't knew about your 10% rule. But when I noticed my hand written notes, it comes somewhere around 10 % of original book. However I personally feel that it's not the 10%, it's the content what you write in your notes is important.Finally, let me explain how I make my notes,Say you are reading a book of 500 pages with 20 units.Split the book into units. Now take unit 1.1. Reading : Read the entire unit. Understand what author is trying to convey. If you don't understand some key points, use internet and understand it properly. By the end of this reading, you will get big picture of what author is explaining and key topics of the unit. 2. Highlight important/key points : While reading, highlight the important points. From next time you can just read highlighted points to recall whole unit.3. Prepare notes : Make the notes based on the highlighted points. You should be able to understand whole picture of the unit by reading these key points in your notes. Repeat same steps for each unit.Now you can just recall the entire book, just by reading your notes. You are finding difficulties during recalling means , you missed some key points. In that case again go back to the book add missed out points. Thank you for reading my answer. Reading method what I explained may not holds good for everyone. If it is useful for you, you can adapt it. I'll be very happy that, my answer helped at-least someone. It's not useful, please just ignore. Do comment if you think it is good/i have to add some point.

No need to make notes for large majority of topics. It is virtually impossible to make notes for such a vast syllabus. Writing down same thing again in a different copy will just waste your precious time.  Just highlight the keywords and phrase from the same book or notes copy and while revising focus on them only.The static topics need to be revised at least three times before appearing for examinations. Write keywords and phrases on the top of the page of all the study material. If you read only those, your study is complete.Don't become depressed and suicidal in the exam hall if you can't remember one or two points from the text you read. Many people even after recalling 9 points out of 10, curse themselves and waste precious time in recalling that point. Hey, there s nothing to get stressed up at it.. just give it a shot. Plan well to study accordingly before u strt ur notes. Keep the following point clear at ur head1) notes r ur backup for last moment study2) notes should be as precise and to the point as possible3) dont add details that would obsess u later while revising4) for 10% i would say.. first select the topic for day and give it a quick reading5) dont mark anything over it.6) now repeat the topic and underline the importants and memorize them7) now give it another attentive reading and out of the underlined ones note down points that u still feel captivating.8) keep them aside n move on to next topic9) read it again later when ur head is all blank about it and u'l see how beneficial it proves to be.10) dont get scared of the process , once u practice it continously it would appear as simple as u wished it to be... :-) it really worked for me... u may give it a try too..All the best..

10% is an arbitrary term,one can just note important lines,or fact.for pre exam one can master by this ,but for mains one has to get thorough knowledge,and there is no short cut here,you have to decide how you take notes,it can be imp lines,10%,25% or whole page.
